        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>East Cliff Lodge\
                Ramsgate 28 Octr 1885<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My dear &#38; respected Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have received a very<lb/> considerable number of<lb/> Letters since the death of my<lb/> lamented Uncle&#44; Sir Moses<lb/> Montefiore&#45;&#45; I sincerely<lb/> assure you that none has<lb/> been more acceptable and<lb/> gratifying to me than the<lb/> Letter you kindly addressed me<lb/> on the 12<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Inst. I am well <lb/> aware that I am quite<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>undeserving of the laudatory<lb/> Terms in which you therein<lb/>speak of me&#8212;Still it has been<lb/> very agreeable to me to read<lb/> your note and to be the recipient<lb/> of the good wishes of so pious and<lb/> esteemed a person as yourself&#45;&#45;<lb/> In your long career in America<lb/> you have indeed evinced a Course <lb/> of conduct alike honorable to<lb/> yourself and Advantageous to<lb/> those who had the good fortune of<lb/> being under your Ministration&#45;&#45;<lb/>And I have frequently felt<lb/> regret that the path of your<lb/> Labors had not continued in this<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Country where&#44; after too short a<lb/> sojourn&#44; you had secured the<lb/> esteem and friendship of those<lb/> with whom you had associated.<lb/> I am very sensible of the honorable<lb/> Inheritance to which I have<lb/> succeeded but I also know my<lb/> weakness and feel much <lb/> apprehension that I must<lb/> necessarily create much<lb/> disappointment. Indeed it would<lb/> be a difficult task for anyone<lb/> worthily to succeed the great and<lb/> good Departed&#45;&#45; I look however with Confidence &#40;as he uniformly<lb/> did&#41; to that great Power&#45;who&#44;<lb/> as declared by Isaiah &#34;giveth<lb/> &#34;strength to the weak.&#34;¬ù<lb/></p>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>As you are doubtless aware<lb/> Sir Moses left a considerable<lb/> part of his Fortune in Legacies<lb/> to Friends and a still larger<lb/> Amount for Charitable purposes<lb/> hence these can be carried out<lb/> by the Authorities&#44; who are the<lb/> Trustees for his benevolent <lb/> Bequests.<lb/></p>
            <p>With much regard<lb/>
                I remain<lb/>
                Yours very truly<lb/>
                Joseph Sebag Montefiore<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My Son desires<lb/>
                His very kind<lb/>
                regards<lb/>
                To <lb/>
                The Revd S. Morais<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="5"/>
            <p>To<lb/>
                The Revd S. Morais<lb/>
                546 N 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                U. S. America<lb/></p>
            </body>
